======================================================================
HOWL PHYS-24: THE CABIBBO DOUBLET
======================================================================

DYNKIN INDEX FORMULAS (Level 1)
----------------------------------------------------------------------

  For a vector-like fermion pair (R_3, R_2, Y):
    Db_1 = (2/5) * dim(R_3) * dim(R_2) * Y^2
    Db_2 = (2/3) * dim(R_3) * S_2(R_2)
    Db_3 = (1/3) * dim(R_2) * S_2(R_3)

  Cabibbo Doublet: (3, 2, 1/6)
      dim(R_3)                             3.0
      dim(R_2)                             2.0
      Y = 1/6                              0.16666666667
      S_2(R_3) = 1/2                       0.5
      S_2(R_2) = 1/2                       0.5

  Computed beta shifts:
      Db_1 = (2/5)*3*2*(1/6)^2 = 1/15      0.066666666667
      Db_2 = (2/3)*3*(1/2) = 1             1.0
      Db_3 = (1/3)*2*(1/2) = 1/3           0.33333333333

  Note: The coefficients (2/5, 2/3, 1/3) are for a complete
  vector-like pair. They are verified by matching the library
  values db_VL = (1/15, 1, 1/3) which produce the gap ratio
  38/27, confirmed by sin2_theta_w_1.py (9/9 checks).

THE Y = 1/6 ASYMMETRY (Level 1)
----------------------------------------------------------------------

  Db_1 depends on Y^2. Db_2 and Db_3 do not.
  At Y = 1/6, Y^2 = 1/36 — a small number.
  This makes Db_1 << Db_2, which is the mechanism
  that pulls the gap ratio DOWN from the SM value.

    Db_2 / Db_1 = 15                       15.0
  The asymmetry ratio is 15: Db_2 is 15 times larger than Db_1.
  This is why (3,2,1/6) fixes the gap ratio — the SU(2) beta
  shifts much more than the U(1) beta.

MODIFIED BETAS: SM + CABIBBO DOUBLET (Level 1)
----------------------------------------------------------------------

  b_1' = b_1 + Db_1 = 25/6                 4.1666666667
  b_2' = b_2 + Db_2 = -13/6                -2.1666666667
  b_3' = b_3 + Db_3 = -20/3                -6.6666666667

  CD gap ratio = 38/27                     1.4074074074

CONFRONTATION: THREE GAP RATIOS (Level 1 vs Derived)
----------------------------------------------------------------------

  SM gap ratio = 218/115                   1.8956521739
    distance from measured (dimensionless) 0.53745948977

  Cabibbo Doublet gap = 38/27              1.4074074074
    distance from measured (dimensionless) 0.049214723263

  MSSM gap ratio = 7/5                     1.4
    distance from measured (dimensionless) 0.041807315855

  Measured gap ratio (Derived)             1.3581926841

  The Cabibbo Doublet (one multiplet, 6 new parameters)
  achieves gap ratio quality comparable to the full MSSM
  (entire superpartner spectrum, 100+ new parameters).

